    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I understand what draws buyers to Coopers Plains and what they expect when they arrive to inspect. The buyer pool here is genuinely mixed: investors working on yield, first-home buyers at the upper edge of their budget, and families who have priced up Robertson or Sunnybank Hills and decided that Coopers Plains gives them what they need at a price that works. Each of those buyer types weighs the property differently, and a campaign that does not speak to that range will leave competition on the table.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Coopers Plains has genuine value drivers that reward precise positioning. Proximity to the train station matters to renters and owner-occupiers alike. Properties with strong rental configurations attract yield-focused investors who are active and decisive when the numbers work. The suburb's location near the Moorooka employment corridor and the major hospital precinct at Woolloongabba creates a tenant base that is stable and consistent, and that story resonates with investors when it is told clearly in the marketing.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
